ssin.  The Bard Chants had gone too far in his pretended allegience to the Wurnqueen.  All of Norrath was in danger.  But who?<br>
<br>
Humwawa sat in cruel silence in Lavastorm.  Cavernous wrinkles crossed his withered face.  Dry wisps of white hair topped his crown.  His clothes weathered and faded, his weapon worn where he held it.  As he spoke to the High Elf messenger, his voice sputtered from his weak, obstructed lungs.  He was tired of it all.<br>
<br>
To kill a friend.  Why?  Why hire Humwawa?  Were there not youthful, eager bloody-mouthed assassins they could hire?  When the messenger plaintively replied it that was a matter of competence, Humwawa hardly listened.  For a howling abivilence overwhelmed him. Why not?  He nodded to the messenger to complete the contract.<br>
<br>
Hours passed.  Humwawa rose up and stared at the night abyss, pounding.  Coughing, he steadied himself with weapon.  Scanning the barren landscape he saw nothing but indifference.  He walked purposelessly to where he knew his friend was to be found, Nagafan's Lair, leaving the large bag of platimum payment behind.<br>
<br>
Upon entering the lair, Chants saw him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Chants,&quot; he gurgled, his raspy voice echoing with the clip-clap of his staff tapping on the hard floor of the lair.  Chants nodded to Humwawa.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why you, mate?&quot;  Chants asked.  Humwawa said nothing as he summoned his obedient lich, Jibantik.  Chants ran to the Lord dragon's chambers.<br>
<br>
A cold, toxic, scream entered the bard's blood and he buckled to his knees.  Then a zinging pulse, and it was gone.<br>
<br>
&quot;Orthodoxy,&quot; said Humwawa with a surprisingly strong voice, &quot;is thy doxy, Chants.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jibantik lunged at Chants engaging him melee.  Shadow step.<br>
<br>
&quot;And Heterodoxy?&quot;  Chants asked his old friend from behind.<br>
<br>
Turning to face him, Humwawa replied, &quot;Is my doxy.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You will not win, Humwawa.  If you beat me, there will be others.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Exactly,&quot; replied Humwawa, as he sent a wretching darkness into Chants' muscles.  <br>
<br>
Shivering and again engaged with the lich in melee, Chants began to lose life rapidly.  Singing was hard.  He shadowstepped again, snared Jibantic and sent a wave of cold, then heat, then magic into the dilapidated necromancer.  Jibantic was loose again, and on Chants hard.<br>
<br>
Atop the wretched chill, another wave of poison chilled Chants.  Humwawa withired stoic.  <br>
<br>
After more than a few minutes elapsed, Chants lay crumpled on the stone floor.  Humwawa limped to the bard's corpse, again, his staff echoing through the chamber.  Silently, he took the dragon egg from Chant's pouch and walked into the Lord dragon's chamber.<br>
<br>
&quot;Assassin, you are bold, but why mock me with your presence?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I mock no one, Lord Nagafan.  Here is your egg,&quot;  Humwawa replied totally viod of any emotion.<br>
<br>
&quot;Veeshan's egg.  With this, it's all over necromancer.  Norrath will never be the same,&quot; the dragon said sternly, as if he were scodling the withered figure before him. <br>
<br>
&quot;Good,&quot;  Humwawa said, smiling.  Turning his back on the dragon, Humwawa, more exhausted and beaten than he had ever looked before, limped away to Chants' corpse.<br>
<br>
Standing next to the bard, the ancient necromancer cast his final spell, filling a large green emerald with his soul.  Dying, he placed the emerald into Chants' pouch whence he took the egg.<br>
<br>
&quot;Take this my friend.&quot;  He said to the corpse.  &quot;And when ye arise, you will find me dead.  But I shall experience the opening of the new world through you.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Thus Humwawa opened the Scars of Velious. <br>
